  "output": "## Scope note\n\nThis isn't a React/frontend codebase — it's a Python async scraper (`fetchers.py`) → filter (`filters.py`) → SQLite dedup store (`store.py`) → notify (`notify.py`) pipeline for job listings, with 114 configured sources (`sources.yaml`), several explicitly noted as \"thousands of roles\" (Microsoft, Amazon, Netflix). So I mapped your five categories onto the Python-equivalent concerns: N+1 → per-row SQL round-trips, re-renders → redundant per-item recomputation, and so on. No React code exists in this repo.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py: Store.diff()` (highest impact)\n\n`diff()` runs one `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop, for every job returned by every fetcher on every run:\n\n```python\n# store.py:59-73\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nWith thousands of roles from boards like Microsoft/Amazon/Netflix, this is thousands of round-trips to SQLite (each with Python↔C driver overhead) instead of one. Fix: batch-load existing hashes into a dict up front, then use `executemany` for the writes:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(cur.execute(q, chunk).fetchall() and\n                         {r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in cur.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, touched, insert_rows, update_rows = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prior = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prior is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif prior != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touched.append(job.key)\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,:source,...,:now,:now)\"\"\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", update_rows)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, k) for k in touched])\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round-trips into O(N/900) + 3 bulk statements.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (`filters.py`)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(include)` / `_compile(exclude)` **inside** that per-job call — so the same include/exclude keyword patterns are recompiled from scratch for every single job in the run:\n\n```python\n# filters.py:11-27 (called once per job)\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFix: compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None, ...) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude, ...)]\n```\n\nFor a run with hundreds/thousands of jobs and several keyword patterns, this eliminates hundreds/thousands of redundant `re.compile` calls.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `Job.key` / `Job.content_hash` recomputed on every access (`models.py`)\n\nBoth are plain `@property`s that recompute from scratch (string join + `sha256`) every time they're read. In `store.py`'s current `diff()`, `job.key` and `job.content_hash` are each computed 2+ times per job (once for the comparison, again inside `to_row()`). Since `Job` fields never mutate after construction, this is safe to memoize. `slots=True` blocks `functools.cached_property`, but you can memoize manually with dedicated slots:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _key: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def key(self) -> str:\n        if self._key is None:\n            self._key = f\"{self.source}:{self.company}:{self.external_id}\"\n        return self._key\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash\n```\nLow-priority on its own (sha256 of a short string is ~microseconds), but combine it with fix #1 and it's free.\n\n## 4. Caching opportunities\n\n- **SQLite write mode**: with bulk upserts (fix #1) happening once per run against thousands of rows, enable WAL + relaxed sync in `Store.__init__` for a meaningful write-throughput win with negligible durability risk for a personal tracker:\n  ```python\n  self.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL\")\n  self.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA synchronous=NORMAL\")\n  ```\n- **`parse_posted_at`**: not cached, but called at most once per job per filter pass — fine as-is, no action needed.\n- Nothing else in the fetch layer is a good caching candidate — job boards change between runs, so re-fetching each run is correct, not wasteful.\n\n## 5. Memory / resource notes\n\nNo real leaks — the codebase is disciplined about closing resources (`with Store(...)`, `client.aclose()` in `fetch_all`'s `finally`). Two minor, low-priority notes:\n\n- **`notify.py`**: `notify_slack`, `notify_webhook`, `notify_sms` each call the blocking `httpx.post(...)` (not `httpx.AsyncClient`) from inside `dispatch()`, which runs inside the async `run()` in `pipeline.py`. It's called once after `fetch_all` completes so it doesn't block concurrent fetches, but it does block the event loop for the duration of each webhook call. Not worth fixing unless you start running other async work concurrently with notification dispatch.\n- **`store.added_since()`**: uses `.fetchall()`, loading every matching row into memory at once. Fine at current scale (`jobs.db` is 348KB); if the tracked table grows into the 100k+ row range, switch to iterating the cursor instead of `fetchall()`.\n\n## Priority order\n\n1. Batch the `store.diff()` N+1 (biggest win, scales with total jobs fetched — thousands per run today).\n2. Precompile filter regex once per run instead of once per job.\n3. Add WAL/synchronous PRAGMAs alongside the batched writes.\n4. Memoize `Job.key`/`content_hash` (cheap, do it while touching `store.diff()`).\n",
